TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Role of Project Completion Information in Resource Allocation Decisions
AU  - Conlon, Donald E.
AU  - Garland, Howard
Y1  - 1993/04/01
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256529
DO  - 10.5465/256529
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 402
EP  - 413
VL  - 36
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Prior studies have suggested that ?sunk costs,? the amount of money already invested in a project, influence resource allocation decisions but have often confounded sunk costs with the degree to which a project is completed. To address this issue, we varied information about both sunk costs and project completion in two experiments. Our results suggest that degree of project completion may dominate any sunk cost effects that are present in resource allocation decisions.
AB  - Prior studies have suggested that ?sunk costs,? the amount of money already invested in a project, influence resource allocation decisions but have often confounded sunk costs with the degree to which a project is completed. To address this issue, we varied information about both sunk costs and project completion in two experiments. Our results suggest that degree of project completion may dominate any sunk cost effects that are present in resource allocation decisions.
